1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,080
You get arrested.

2
00:00:01,880 --> 00:00:05,966
Maybe it is serious, maybe it is a mistake —

3
00:00:06,040 --> 00:00:07,860
it does not matter yet,

4
00:00:08,340 --> 00:00:10,540
because you have not been tried,

5
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:12,220
let alone convicted.

6
00:00:13,300 --> 00:00:17,500
And during booking, an officer runs a cotton swab along

7
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:19,180
the inside of your cheek,

8
00:00:19,660 --> 00:00:24,320
reads your DNA, and enters your genetic code into a

9
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:27,798
national database that is searched against unsolved crimes .

10
00:00:28,900 --> 00:00:31,560
In 2013, by a single vote,

11
00:00:32,120 --> 00:00:34,620
the Supreme Court said they are allowed to do that.

12
00:00:38,080 --> 00:00:41,440
The Fourth Amendment is supposed to stop the government from

13
00:00:41,440 --> 00:00:45,220
searching you for evidence of a crime unless it has

14
00:00:45,220 --> 00:00:50,675
a specific reason to suspect you of that crime .

15
00:00:50,676 --> 00:00:53,220
But there is an exception built into being arrested: the

16
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:56,940
booking process, where the police fingerprint you and

17
00:00:56,940 --> 00:00:59,200
photograph you to confirm who you are.

18
00:00:59,920 --> 00:01:03,340
The question in this case was whether a DNA swab

19
00:01:03,340 --> 00:01:06,771
belongs in that box —

20
00:01:06,772 --> 00:01:09,588
a routine way to identify you —

21
00:01:09,589 --> 00:01:11,760
or whether it is something else: a search of your

22
00:01:11,760 --> 00:01:15,560
body for evidence of crimes no one has accused you

23
00:01:15,560 --> 00:01:16,100
of.

24
00:01:16,380 --> 00:01:19,980
Over the next twelve minutes: the cheek swab,

25
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:22,200
the cold case it cracked,

26
00:01:22,680 --> 00:01:25,480
and the deep, unusual split it caused.

27
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:30,240
In 2009, a man named Alonzo King is arrested in

28
00:01:30,240 --> 00:01:30,560
Maryland.

29
00:01:31,180 --> 00:01:32,495
The charge is assault —

30
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:35,880
he had menaced a group of people with a shotgun

31
00:01:36,372 --> 00:01:36,652
.

32
00:01:36,680 --> 00:01:40,120
That arrest is based on its own facts; it has

33
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:41,960
nothing to do with what follows.

34
00:01:43,080 --> 00:01:45,180
During booking, under a Maryland law,

35
00:01:45,660 --> 00:01:48,620
the police take a cheek swab and record his DNA

36
00:01:49,369 --> 00:01:49,649
.

37
00:01:49,650 --> 00:01:53,480
This is the key detail to hold onto: the swab

38
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:55,180
is not why he was arrested.

39
00:01:55,880 --> 00:01:58,960
It is a routine step the state applies to people

40
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:00,600
arrested for serious crimes.

41
00:02:01,480 --> 00:02:04,640
His DNA profile goes into the database.

42
00:02:05,140 --> 00:02:08,680
And there, it matches genetic evidence left at the scene

43
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:10,438
of a rape from 2003 —

44
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:13,871
a case that had gone unsolved for years .

45
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:16,360
On the strength of that match,

46
00:02:16,820 --> 00:02:18,380
King is charged with that rape,

47
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:21,119
and he is convicted of it .

48
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:24,660
So look at what just happened from two different angles,

49
00:02:24,700 --> 00:02:28,160
because the whole case lives in the gap between them.

50
00:02:29,100 --> 00:02:32,900
From one angle: a violent crime that had gone cold

51
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:35,000
for six years was finally solved,

52
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:37,640
and a rapist was held accountable,

53
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:40,540
because of a swab taken at booking.

54
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:44,240
From the other angle: the government took a sample of

55
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:45,605
a man's body —

56
00:02:45,606 --> 00:02:48,670
before he had been convicted of anything —

57
00:02:48,880 --> 00:02:52,100
and used it to search for his connection to an

58
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:55,949
entirely different crime he was not suspected of .

59
00:02:56,140 --> 00:02:57,820
Both descriptions are true.

60
00:02:58,460 --> 00:03:00,480
That is what makes the case hard.

61
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:04,400
To decide it, the Court had to answer a deceptively

62
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:07,880
simple question: what is a DNA swab,

63
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:08,240
legally?

64
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:10,560
Is it more like a fingerprint,

65
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:12,240
or more like a search?

66
00:03:13,240 --> 00:03:16,420
Think about what already happens when you are booked.

67
00:03:17,100 --> 00:03:19,860
The police take your fingerprints and your photograph.

68
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:22,480
Courts have long allowed this,

69
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:24,770
because its purpose is identification —

70
00:03:26,100 --> 00:03:28,960
confirming that the person in the cell is who they

71
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:32,860
say they are, and checking whether they are wanted elsewhere

72
00:03:33,102 --> 00:03:33,382
.

73
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:36,520
It is not treated as a search for evidence,

74
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:40,180
because that is not really what it is for.

75
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,560
The state argued DNA is just the next step in

76
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:47,207
that same process —

77
00:03:47,208 --> 00:03:49,080
the fingerprint of the twenty-first century.

78
00:03:49,760 --> 00:03:52,360
A cheek swab is quick and barely physical.

79
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:55,500
And like a fingerprint, the state said,

80
00:03:56,040 --> 00:04:00,300
it identifies the arrestee, and it can be checked against

81
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:01,599
records —

82
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:04,652
including the records of unsolved crimes .

83
00:04:04,940 --> 00:04:07,360
But critics, and four of the justices,

84
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:12,140
saw a sleight of hand in that word "identification." A

85
00:04:12,140 --> 00:04:16,480
fingerprint taken at booking is mostly used to confirm who

86
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:17,940
you are right now.

87
00:04:19,020 --> 00:04:23,340
DNA, in practice, was being used for something different: to

88
00:04:23,340 --> 00:04:26,880
run the arrestee against a national database of crime-scene

89
00:04:27,220 --> 00:04:31,234
evidence, looking for hits .

90
00:04:31,235 --> 00:04:34,098
That database has a name —

91
00:04:34,099 --> 00:04:37,439
CODIS, the FBI's national DNA index —

92
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:41,280
and the whole value of swabbing arrestees comes from

93
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:44,599
searching it against cold cases .

94
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:45,820
If that is the purpose,

95
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:51,020
the dissent argued, then it is not really "identification"

96
00:04:51,020 --> 00:04:51,720
at all.

97
00:04:52,520 --> 00:04:55,340
It is a search of your body for evidence of

98
00:04:55,340 --> 00:04:57,964
crime —

99
00:04:57,965 --> 00:05:00,300
exactly the thing the Fourth Amendment normally forbids

100
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:03,691
without individualized suspicion .

101
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:06,400
There was also a quieter worry underneath.

102
00:05:07,260 --> 00:05:11,100
A fingerprint reveals almost nothing about you except its

103
00:05:11,100 --> 00:05:11,840
own pattern.

104
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:13,932
DNA is different —

105
00:05:14,540 --> 00:05:17,480
it is a blueprint that can expose your relatives,

106
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:20,860
your health, your most private traits.

107
00:05:21,840 --> 00:05:25,080
The majority stressed that the law used only a narrow

108
00:05:25,080 --> 00:05:28,900
set of identifying markers, not your whole genome.

109
00:05:30,280 --> 00:05:33,220
Critics answered that the physical sample itself is kept,

110
00:05:33,820 --> 00:05:36,340
and that the line the state draws today,

111
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:39,073
it can quietly move tomorrow .

112
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:43,200
In 2013, the Supreme Court upheld the swab.

113
00:05:43,920 --> 00:05:45,600
By a vote of five to four,

114
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,680
it held that taking a DNA cheek swab from someone

115
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:51,620
arrested for a serious offense,

116
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:54,120
as part of routine booking,

117
00:05:54,460 --> 00:05:58,057
is a reasonable search under the Fourth Amendment .

118
00:05:58,340 --> 00:06:01,840
The opinion was written by Justice Anthony Kennedy.

119
00:06:02,700 --> 00:06:06,387
The intrusion, he reasoned, is minimal —

120
00:06:06,420 --> 00:06:09,240
a brief, gentle swab of the cheek.

121
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:14,380
And the government's interests are strong: identifying who

122
00:06:14,380 --> 00:06:17,200
is in custody, knowing their history,

123
00:06:17,640 --> 00:06:21,180
and the broader public-safety value of the DNA system.

124
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:25,820
Weigh the small intrusion against the large interest,

125
00:06:26,380 --> 00:06:30,120
the majority concluded, and the swab is reasonable.

126
00:06:30,940 --> 00:06:32,840
It is, in the Court's words,

127
00:06:33,460 --> 00:06:36,923
like fingerprinting and photographing —

128
00:06:36,924 --> 00:06:39,602
a legitimate booking procedure .

129
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:44,480
Kennedy also spelled out what "identification" meant to the

130
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:47,600
majority, and it was broader than a name.

131
00:06:48,920 --> 00:06:50,780
Knowing an arrestee's full history,

132
00:06:51,080 --> 00:06:55,420
the Court said, helps officers judge how dangerous he might

133
00:06:55,420 --> 00:06:58,100
be, whether he is a flight risk,

134
00:06:58,100 --> 00:07:01,260
and whether he threatens the people around him.

135
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,159
DNA, in that view, was not a fishing expedition —

136
00:07:05,860 --> 00:07:09,660
it was part of safely processing a person already in

137
00:07:09,660 --> 00:07:11,338
the state's custody .

138
00:07:11,420 --> 00:07:14,600
The dissent was sharp, and it came from an unusual

139
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:15,200
place.

140
00:07:16,340 --> 00:07:19,377
Justice Antonin Scalia wrote it —

141
00:07:19,378 --> 00:07:21,660
and he was joined not by his usual allies,

142
00:07:22,260 --> 00:07:24,640
but by three of the Court's liberal justices,

143
00:07:25,660 --> 00:07:29,334
Ginsburg, Sotomayor, and Kagan .

144
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:33,040
When the most conservative and the most liberal justices

145
00:07:33,040 --> 00:07:36,220
line up together, it is worth paying attention.

146
00:07:37,660 --> 00:07:39,100
Scalia's argument was direct.

147
00:07:39,750 --> 00:07:44,400
The swab, he said, was not really about identifying Alonzo

148
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:45,050
King —

149
00:07:45,900 --> 00:07:47,920
the police already knew who he was.

150
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:51,580
Its purpose was to investigate unsolved crimes,

151
00:07:52,380 --> 00:07:56,340
and the Constitution does not allow the government to search

152
00:07:56,340 --> 00:07:59,900
a person for evidence of crime without a reason to

153
00:07:59,900 --> 00:08:00,731
suspect them of it .

154
00:08:01,620 --> 00:08:04,480
And he ended with a warning that has been quoted

155
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:08,300
ever since: as a consequence of this decision,

156
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:13,020
he wrote, your DNA can be taken and entered into

157
00:08:13,020 --> 00:08:16,540
a national DNA database if you are ever arrested,

158
00:08:16,860 --> 00:08:20,040
rightly or wrongly, and for whatever reason.

159
00:08:20,980 --> 00:08:23,820
He felt strongly enough that he read a summary of

160
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:26,617
his dissent aloud from the bench —

161
00:08:26,618 --> 00:08:30,540
something justices do only for the rulings they most oppose

162
00:08:31,005 --> 00:08:31,285
.

163
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:33,100
So here is where it leaves you.

164
00:08:33,100 --> 00:08:34,820
In much of the country,

165
00:08:35,220 --> 00:08:38,760
being arrested for a serious offense now means giving a

166
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:41,924
DNA sample —

167
00:08:41,925 --> 00:08:43,600
taken before any trial, kept in a database,

168
00:08:44,200 --> 00:08:47,682
and searched against unsolved crimes .

169
00:08:47,683 --> 00:08:50,240
The exact rules vary from state to state,

170
00:08:50,680 --> 00:08:54,280
but the principle the Supreme Court blessed is the same

171
00:08:54,280 --> 00:08:54,800
everywhere.

172
00:08:55,680 --> 00:08:58,540
And the honest truth is that both sides of this

173
00:08:58,540 --> 00:09:00,200
were right about something real.

174
00:09:00,770 --> 00:09:06,160
The system genuinely works: DNA databases have closed cold

175
00:09:06,160 --> 00:09:10,500
cases, freed innocent people, and identified violent

176
00:09:10,500 --> 00:09:12,834
offenders who would otherwise have walked free .

177
00:09:13,860 --> 00:09:15,580
That is not a small thing.

178
00:09:16,540 --> 00:09:19,500
But it is also true that the people swept into

179
00:09:19,500 --> 00:09:22,860
those databases include the merely arrested —

180
00:09:23,340 --> 00:09:26,460
people charged with something and later cleared,

181
00:09:27,220 --> 00:09:28,091
people arrested by mistake —

182
00:09:29,660 --> 00:09:32,640
whose genetic code is now on file because of a

183
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:35,065
single encounter with the police .

184
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:37,460
That is the trade the Court made,

185
00:09:37,460 --> 00:09:42,380
by one vote: a powerful tool against serious crime,

186
00:09:43,060 --> 00:09:47,080
paid for with the genetic privacy of everyone an officer

187
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:48,220
decides to arrest.

188
00:09:49,040 --> 00:09:52,280
Whether that trade is worth it is exactly the kind

189
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:56,382
of question the Constitution is supposed to answer —

190
00:09:56,960 --> 00:09:59,280
and here, it split the Court down the middle,

191
00:09:59,280 --> 00:10:01,460
across every usual line.

192
00:10:02,280 --> 00:10:05,240
A cheek swab taken at a booking desk solved a

193
00:10:05,240 --> 00:10:07,939
six-year-old crime —

194
00:10:07,940 --> 00:10:09,020
and, in the same motion,

195
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:12,580
redrew the line around the most personal thing you own:

196
00:10:13,160 --> 00:10:17,286
the code inside your own cells .

197
00:10:17,287 --> 00:10:17,620
The Court called it a fingerprint.

198
00:10:18,220 --> 00:10:20,900
Four justices called it a search.

199
00:10:22,260 --> 00:10:25,060
The difference between those two words is the difference

200
00:10:25,060 --> 00:10:28,460
between identifying you and investigating you.

201
00:10:29,220 --> 00:10:32,040
We have followed the state as it reaches into your

202
00:10:32,040 --> 00:10:35,200
pockets, your phone, your property,

203
00:10:35,780 --> 00:10:38,020
your contracts, and now your body.

204
00:10:38,980 --> 00:10:42,840
Each time, a power that began small is stretched to

205
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:45,397
fit a world the founders never saw —

206
00:10:45,860 --> 00:10:49,520
and each time, a court has to decide how far

207
00:10:49,520 --> 00:10:50,280
is too far.

208
00:10:51,080 --> 00:10:53,560
But there is one place that has always been the

209
00:10:53,560 --> 00:10:57,528
strongest fortress of all —

210
00:10:57,529 --> 00:10:58,800
the one the law guards most jealously,

211
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:02,940
where you are supposed to be safest from the state:

212
00:11:03,840 --> 00:11:04,740
your own home.

213
00:11:05,760 --> 00:11:08,460
So what happens when a police officer,

214
00:11:08,460 --> 00:11:10,940
chasing you for something minor,

215
00:11:11,580 --> 00:11:14,475
follows you right up to your door —

216
00:11:14,476 --> 00:11:15,700
and you step inside?

217
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:18,100
Can they come in after you,

218
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:18,900
without a warrant?

219
00:11:19,960 --> 00:11:21,100
That is next time.
